<div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">Macbee wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What happens when you use a horizontally-stretched checkerboard pattern?<br /><br />For instance, two columns for every row, or three columns for every row:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">xx  xx<br />  xx  xx<br />xx  xx<br /><br /><br />xxx   xxx<br />   xxx   xxx<br />xxx   xxx</div><br /><br />This seems like it'd be a good compromise between the two methods.<br /></div></div><br /><br />Nice suggestion Drag! I've tried it and the results are good.<br />There are noticeable artifacts on background - but it's hard to see them on Iceman's body (where similar colors are flickered). Sretched checkerboard patterns looks better (than regular checkerboard ones) when using composite cables IMO.<br /><br /><a href="http://s5.beta.photobucket.com/user/macbee/media/iceman_zpsb61d8155.jpg.html" class="postlink"><img src="http://i5.photobucket.com/albums/y191/macbee/th_iceman_zpsb61d8155.jpg" alt="Image" /></a><br /><br />I'm attaching 3 Iceman roms here - each one made with a different flickering technique (lines, checkerboard and stretched checkerboard).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5106">Macbee</a> — Sun Jan 13, 2013 9:20 am</p><hr />
