<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9674&amp;p=105885#p105885"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">Macbee wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><strong>1) Checkerboard patterns -</strong><br />Pros: It's the ultimate flicker technique to make good looking images. Results are usually impressive.<br />Cons: Diagonal artifacts seems to be present all the time when using Composite cables, no matter how similar flickered colors are.<br /><br /><strong>2) Horizontal lines patterns -</strong><br />Pros: It's the only flicker technique that doesn't seem to create diagonal artifacts when using Composite cables.<br />Cons: End results doesn't look as good as checkerboard flickered images (shakiness is way more evident).<br /></div><br /><br />What happens when you use a horizontally-stretched checkerboard pattern?<br /><br />For instance, two columns for every row, or three columns for every row:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">xx  xx<br />  xx  xx<br />xx  xx<br /><br /><br />xxx   xxx<br />   xxx   xxx<br />xxx   xxx</div><br /><br />This seems like it'd be a good compromise between the two methods.</div><br /><br />Unfortunately, this ends up looking less like blended colors and more like a stretched checkerboard at that point.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5314">mikejmoffitt</a> — Thu Jan 10, 2013 1:46 pm</p><hr />
